OK, that should be enough.

Rowling was doing so *well* until the very ending.  I was really
engaged, had to force myself to put the book down so I could get a
couple hourse of sleep before going to work.  Then came the ending, and
it just didn't make any sense.

The deathly hallows themselves seem to be nothing but misdirection.
Harry was carrying one of them on his way to meet Voldemort--the
invisibility cloak--but wasn't wearing it.  He acquired another on the
way, then dropped it before the meeting.  The whole bit with the Elder
Wand (see below) was confused and bogus.  Apparently the hallows had
nothing to do with him surviving Voldemort's Avada Kedavra.

The bit in &quot;King's Cross&quot; seemed a deus ex machina, unworthy of the
series as it has been written so far.  But I guess that's just my
opinion.

Harry had put his mother's type of protection on *everybody*?  Lame.

But worst of all was the business of the wands.  Harry says that Draco
was the true master of the Elder wand--huh?  Why?  But then he says that
because he took Draco's wand--that would be Draco's original wand, the
one he used throughout Hogwarts, right?--that makes him the true master
of the Elder Wand?  Whaa?  An Avada Kedavra bounces off of a
Expelliarmus?  Since when?  This is the spell that cannot be blocked,
right?

THEN, when V is dead, we hear *nothing* more about the many Death Eaters
scattered about who will be fighting for their lives.  And consider
this:  The ministry was run by pureblood biggots.  Only some of them
were Death Eaters; the ministry had been able to implement sweeping
anti-mudblood measures only because there were so many like-thinking
wizards either already in the bureaucracy (like Umbridge) or who could
be easily recruited.  That machinery was running quite well without
Voldemort, as Voldemort ran around hunting wands.  The biggoted
Ministry, with its considerable resources and mantle of legitimacy,
still remains after the battle.  Those who collaborated have a vested
interest in at least pretending that they still believe in those
principals.

