On Jul 26, 9:31 am, nos ... @nospam.com (Paul Ciszek) wrote:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; The deathly hallows themselves seem to be nothing but misdirection.
">

It served several purposes.  The most important is that it gave
Harry Potter a choice.  Wouldn't the book have been boring if
it merely chronicled his robotic obedience to Dumbledore's
orders to track down the Horcruxes?  This gave Harry meaningful
decisions to make.

In addition, the Horcruxes gave Voldemort something to
obsess over while Harry was on his quest.  Otherwise, it
would have just been Voldemort and his forces chasing
down Harry for the whole book--again, not so interesting.

Third, it gave Dumbledore a fatal flaw.  It was Dumbledore's
obsession with the Hallows that caused his downfall.

All in all, I'd say it was a pretty neat job of Rowling to get
so much mileage out of the Deathly Hallows.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; The bit in &quot;King's Cross&quot; seemed a deus ex machina, unworthy of the
&gt; series as it has been written so far.  But I guess that's just my
&gt; opinion.
">

You're forgetting the final twist, which was that it was all
in Harry's head.  That wasn't actually Dumbledore, it was
Harry's subconscious figuring out what he could based
on what he knew at the time (and getting some of it
wrong).

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; An Avada Kedavra bounces off of a
&gt; Expelliarmus?  Since when?
">

Since always, when the two wizards involved are
Harry Potter and Lord Voldemort.  There were actually
a number of things which would cause Voldemort's
killing spell to fail.  It was like Voldemort was caught
in a triple-checkmate.  Voldemort by this point was
well and thoroughly beaten--and he knew it, even
if he didn't know exactly all the reasons why.

Isaac Kuo
